<div class="sqs-html-content" data-sqsp-text-block-content><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><a href="https://open.spotify.com/artist/4kn6OXcs3RVTYeJh15pMmw?si=iuCLmwkpQ_uwZD_jO6pe-A" target="_blank"><strong>RiotWeekend</strong> </a>kicked things off with a tight, high-energy set. The Guildford-based four-piece, fronted by a commanding lead vocalist, wasted no time getting the crowd moving. Their originals were punchy and well-rehearsed, and the inclusion of a <em>“American Idiot”</em> cover landed well with early punters. All four members contributed vocals, which gave the set a full, dynamic sound. Some sharp crowd work and a lot of chemistry between bandmates made them one of the most confident openers of the night.</p><p class="" data-rte-preserve-empty="true" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"></p></div>

