</div>
<div class="sqs-html-content" data-sqsp-text-block-content><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><a href="https://open.spotify.com/artist/7EO7fbNcE00PlD59wZIZSY?si=v7Fk24cWTrGVOyv18TkC1g" target="_blank"><strong>Spank Hair</strong></a> switched things up with a looser, more melodic approach. Formed out of Oxford’s DIY scene, they played through a warm, scrappy set of emo-leaning indie rock. <em>“Claws”</em> and <em>“See You in the Morning”</em> set the tone early, and the short, catchy <em>“Tony Hawk”</em> — dedicated to Bulgarelli — got a good laugh. The highlight might’ve been <em>“Cowboy Scene”</em>, led by the drummer on vocals, which brought a moment of sincerity to an otherwise playful set. A couple of tech issues aside, they handled things well and finished strong with <em>“Many Phones Ago”</em>.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></p></div>

